Mujica travels to Mexico for the stabilization of the political relations
An official delegation, aforementioned of the Uruguayan president José Mujica and consisting of several Ministers and entrepreneur starts its visit of Mexico on Tuesday, in order to expand the trade between both countries and to discuss political topics of the region
Mujica meets on next Wednesday with his Mexican colleague Felipe Calderón. That will be according to the Uruguayan president the high point of its written off schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of the Uruguayer living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city Guadalajara “is suitable for the exchange of information about all politics ranges between the two countries”, announced the presidential office of the South American country on its website.
According to local media look for Mujica the support Calderóns regarding the incident with France, when the French head of government Nicolas Sarkozy set the South American country on the summit of the G20 in the French city Cannes on a list with tax havens.
In its discourse Sarkozy thereby threatened to exclude those countries, which appear still as tax havens, from the international community. This explanation was rejected by Uruguay and arranged an inquiry with its Ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has the presidency of the G20, a group for November consisting of the most powerful swelling and industrialized countries of the world. Since January of this year an agreement exists over the exchange from control information to the avoidance of the double assessment with the South American country.
The government of Uruguay tried in the last years to accelerate the concretisation of agreements for the change from control information to in order from the “grey list” of the organization for economic co-operation and development (OECD) to be painted. Whereupon stand countries, which introduced not all international standards to co-operation into tax affairs.
On business level a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay since 2004, which contributed to an increasing exchange of goods between the two countries, insists.
